<CENTER>
<H1>Some disasters attributable to bad numerical computing</H1></CENTER>
<P>Have you been paying attention in your numerical analysis or =
scientific=20
computation courses? If not, it could be a costly mistake. Here are some =
real=20
life examples of what can happen when numerical algorithms are not =
correctly=20
applied.=20
<P>The <A =
href=3D"http://www.ima.umn.edu/~arnold/disasters/patriot.html">Patriot=20
Missile failure</A>, in Dharan, Saudi Arabia, on February 25, 1991 which =

resulted in 28 deaths, is ultimately attributable to poor handling of =
rounding=20
errors.=20
<P>The <A =
href=3D"http://www.ima.umn.edu/~arnold/disasters/ariane.html">explosion=20
of the Ariane 5 rocket</A> just after lift-off on its maiden voyage off =
French=20
Guiana, on June 4, 1996, was ultimately the consequence of a simple =
overflow.=20
<P>The <A =
href=3D"http://www.ima.umn.edu/~arnold/disasters/sleipner.html">sinking=20
of the Sleipner A offshore platform</A> in Gandsfjorden near Stavanger, =
Norway,=20
on August 23, 1991, resulted in a loss of nearly one billion dollars. It =
was=20
found to be the result of inaccurate finite element analysis.=20
<P>
